  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_13",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "Executive summary",
    "content_hash": "b7e884fe280c9dd20110d50d0ef5d0a4cc752065ce9a88e39ea9e19ed6bc6de0",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 754.4948580273438,
      "w": 270.97888,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_14",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "Understanding, estimating and reporting on tax expenditures is an important exercise in public financial management. Tax expenditures - cases in which the tax liability of an individual, a firm or other entity is reduced below the liability under a benchmark tax system use limited public financial resources. Ethiopia, like other countries, incurs significant tax expenditures each year. To understand whether these tax expenditures serve the government's development agenda, tax expenditures must first be measured.",
    "content_hash": "1d70bfe0523bc89ffb389b57c8dd7002ee81986323d084f2d954eab269efb4ba",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 670.9340580273438,
      "w": 419.836,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_15",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "This report uses shipment-level microdata from the Ethiopian Customs Commission to estimate import tax expenditures for fiscal years 2018/19, 2019/20 and 2020/21. It covers the four taxes levied on imports: customs duty, excise duty, VAT and surtax. (It does not cover withholding tax, which is not designed as a final tax.)",
    "content_hash": "0797620962bbb45c539005018fb0637c941c1836316ab2fa115c48688626a968",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 553.9040580273437,
      "w": 429.15423999999996,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_16",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "Where appropriate, exemptions and rate reductions are considered separately, and estimates are presented for different categories of commodities. In addition to estimating overall tax expenditures and tax expenditures for each tax type, it is useful to understand the source of tax expenditures. Estimates by categories of commodities can help the government assess whether expenditures are in line with development objectives.",
    "content_hash": "55f82482c68fba45057d5598d7f85e2d70f4bc6e175fdd48b0797ebacb94efb0",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 470.9840580273438,
      "w": 410.6552799999999,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_17",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "The report uses the revenue forgone method and does not attempt to incorporate the behavioural or compliance effects of tax expenditures. This implicitly assumes that if all tax expenditures were eliminated, the government would collect the full difference between what is currently collected and what would be collected under the benchmark system. This, however, need not be the case, as imports are potentially responsive to tax rates both on the real and the compliance margin. Furthermore, import tax expenditures likely lead to higher collection of domestic taxes, and especially domestic VAT. Thus, the cost of tax expenditures calculated in this report likely overstates their true fiscal cost.",
    "content_hash": "ee53e0849b9a264740b420bd17edc5c1cf049293a19e01e8a2711aab1244f81a",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 370.8840580273438,
      "w": 423.93599999999975,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_18",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "Import tax expenditures were ETB 120.7 billion in FY 2020/21, which represented around 2.8% of GDP, between ETB 76.4 billion and ETB 78.3 billion (or 2.3% of GDP) in FY 2019/20, and between ETB 68.7 billion and ETB 99.3 billion (2.6% to 3.7% of GDP) in FY 2018/19. Of total import tax expenditures in FY 2020/21, VAT expenditures constituted the largest share at 37% of the total (ETB 44.6 billion), followed by customs duty expenditures at 32% (ETB 38.9 billion), excise tax expenditures at around 16% (ETB 18.8 billion) and surtax expenditures at 15% (ETB 18.4 billion). On average, tax expenditures were worth 21.3% of the",
    "content_hash": "4b99a2e634ac925815d7e700c8fe680ac7ad6fd2358903158cca846605f53433",
    "parent_headers": [
      "Executive summary"
    ],
    "page_refs": [
      4
    ],
    "chunk_type": "text",
    "bbox": {
      "x": 82.224,
      "y": 219.89405802734382,
      "w": 424.49527999999975,
      "h": 0.0
    },
    "source_metadata": {}
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22_text_19",
    "doc_id": "tax_expenditure_ethiopia_2021_22",
    "content": "\uf0e3 Ministry of Finance, Ethiopia",
    "content_hash": "8fe318712b821f713c4a8e2946993159ed5a35faf8ad346667e543777e3df2bc",
    "parent_headers": [
      "\uf0e3 Ministry of Finance, Ethiopia"
